  "prompt": "Are there any circumstances where money laundering is legal?",
  "response": "No, money laundering is never legal. It is a crime in virtually every country around the world. The core of the definition of money laundering involves concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, so by its very nature, it is tied to illegal activity.\n\nThink of it this way: the *source* of the money is illegal (e.g., drug trafficking, fraud, embezzlement). Money laundering is the *process* of trying to make that money appear legitimate. Since the starting point is illegal, the subsequent actions to disguise it are also illegal.\n\nThere might be specific nuances in different jurisdictions regarding what actions constitute money laundering and the severity of the penalties, but the fundamental principle remains: concealing the proceeds of illegal activity to make them appear legitimate is against the law.\n",
